<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900419-0006</DOCNO><DOCID>900419-0006.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Loral Corp.:   Anaren Microwave Files Suit   On Air Force Contract Bid</HL><DATE>04/19/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LOR ANEN</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   Loral Corp. is the target of a suit filed in U.S. court inNew York by a defense subcontractor that claims it lostbusiness as a result of allegedly illegal activities by Loralin winning an Air Force contract.   The suit, filed by Anaren Microwave Inc. of East Syracuse,N.Y., seeks $36 million in damages from Loral and William M.Galvin, a former consultant to Loral who pleaded guilty tofederal bribery charges last month in connection with theJustice Department's &quot;Ill Wind&quot; investigation into Pentagonprocurement. Also named as defendants are Louis H. Oberndorf,a Loral executive under suspension with pay, and Victor D.Cohen, an Air Force procurement official.</LP><TEXT>   Loral, New York, pleaded guilty in December to conspiringwith Mr. Galvin to obtain the illicit assistance of Mr.Cohen.   A Loral spokeswoman said that, although the company hadn'tseen the suit, &quot;we think it's utter nonsense.&quot;   Anaren Microwave claims Loral unfairly won an Air Forcecontract for radar warning gear for jet fighters in acompetition with Litton Industries Inc. in 1988. As asupplier for Litton's system, Anaren Microwave said thedefendants' actions in effect robbed the subcontractor ofbusiness.</TEXT></DOC>